\begin_layout Subsection*

Uniqueness of the Color-Matching Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Suppose two research groups measure the color-matching functions using different sets of primary lights. One group measures the color-matching functions using three primary lights 
\begin_inset Formula $\primaryi{i}$
\end_inset

, while the second group uses a different set of primary lights, 
\begin_inset Formula $\primaryi{i}'$
\end_inset

. Because the groups use different primary lights, they will measure different sets of color-matching functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Photopic$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Photopic '$
\end_inset

. How will the two sets of color matching functions be related?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

We can answer this question by the following thought experiment. First, create a matrix whose columns contain the spectral power distributions of the first group's primary lights, and call this matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Primarymat$
\end_inset

. The spectral power distribution of a mixture of the primaries, with primary intensities 
\begin_inset Formula $\primaryint$
\end_inset

 is the weighted sum of the columns. We can express this mixture using the matrix product 
\begin_inset Formula $\Primarymat \primaryint$
\end_inset

. Now, we can use the color-matching functions to predict when a test light light will match the mixture of three primaries. The test and primaries will match when 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{e3:match1}
\Photopic \test = \Photopic \Primarymat \primaryint .
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Suppose the second group of researchers can also established matches to this test light using their primaries. To describe their measurements, we create a second matrix whose columns contain the spectral power distributions of the second group's primary lights, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Primarymat '$
\end_inset

. Call the primary intensities used to match the test with the second primaries is 
\begin_inset Formula $\primaryint '$
\end_inset

. Since the light 
\begin_inset Formula $\Primarymat ' \primaryint '$
\end_inset

 is a visual matched to the test light, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{e3:match2}
\Photopic \test = \Photopic \Primarymat ' \primaryint '
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 By combining Equations
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "e3:match1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "e3:match2"

\end_inset

, we find that the two vectors of primary intensities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\primaryint$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\primaryint '$
\end_inset

, are related by a linear transformation, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\primaryint = 
  (\Photopic \Primarymat )^{-1}\Photopic \Primarymat ' \primaryint ' .
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Finally, recall that the vectors in the columns of the color-matching functions are the primary intensity settings necessary to match the monochromatic lights. We have just shown that the primary intensities used to make matches with the two different sets of primaries are related by a linear transformation. Hence, the system matrices containing the color-matching functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Photopic$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Photopic '$
\end_inset

 must be related a linear transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

With a little more algebra, one can show that the color-matching functions are related by the following linear transformation: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Photopic = ( \Photopic \Primarymat ' ) \Photopic ' .
\end{equation}
