\begin_layout Subsection*

Static Nonlinearities: The principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

We can analyze the photopigment sensitivity from the photocurrent response because the nonlinear relationship between the test light and the photocurrent signal is very simple: The photons are absorbed by a linear process; the linear encoding is followed by a nonlinear process that converts the photopigment absorption rate into membrane photocurrent. The properties of the nonlinear process are independent of the linear encoding step, and thus we call this process a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 static nonlinearity
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

. When a system is a linear process followed by a static nonlinearity, we can characterize the system performance completely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

It is worth spending a little time thinking about why we can characterize this type of nonlinear system. First, consider the linear process of photopigment absorption. There is a photopigment system matrix, say, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rhodopsin$
\end_inset

, that maps the test light into a photon absorption rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rhodopsin \test$
\end_inset

. Second, the static nonlinearity converts the photopigment absorption rate into a peak photocurrent response. Together, these two processes define the nonlinear system response, 
\begin_inset Formula $F( \Rhodopsin \test )$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

When we set a match between the peak photocurrent from the test light and the primary light, we establish an equation of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F( \Rhodopsin \test) = F( a \Rhodopsin \primary ),
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the intensity of the primary light needed to match the test light. Since the nonlinear function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is monotonic, we can remove it from both sides of the Equation and write 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{e3:static.homogeneity}
\Rhodopsin \test = a \Rhodopsin \primary .
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 From this equation we see that there is a linear relationship between the primary and test light intensities, since if 
\begin_inset Formula $\test$
\end_inset

 matches 
\begin_inset Formula $a \primary$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $k \test$
\end_inset

 will match 
\begin_inset Formula $k a \primary$
\end_inset

. Thus, even if a system has a static nonlinearity, the system's performance in a matching experiment will satisfy the test of homogeneity. We can also show that in a matching experiment a system with a static nonlinearity will satisfy superposition.
\end_layout

